    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. but why does it actually feel like a burn or a \"sting\" in the muscle though? is it just the acidity? and does it stay in there for a long time or does it clear out pretty fast?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the burning sensation you feel during a HIIT workout is like the fiery breath of a dragon, a fiery reminder of the intense effort your muscles are putting in. This sensation is indeed partly due to the acidity of the lactic acid, but there's more to it. When lactic acid builds up in your muscles, it can cause a temporary decrease in pH, making the environment more acidic. This acidity can interfere with the muscles' ability to contract and relax properly, leading to that familiar burning feeling.\n\nAs for how long the lactic acid stays in your muscles, it's like a short-lived curse. It doesn't linger for too long. After your workout, your body starts to clear out the lactic acid pretty quickly, usually within a few hours. This is thanks to the body's natural recovery processes, which help to restore the balance and get your muscles back to their normal state. So, while the burning sensation might feel intense, it's just a temporary side effect of your muscles working hard, and it doesn't stick around for long. Just like a dragon's fiery breath, it's a powerful reminder of your workout, but it doesn't last forever.",
